r\n some previously offered material covered by poornahuti) could not burn wel=\r\nl. In general, smoke is a sign that fire tried to reach/consume some parts =\r\nbut was unable to.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;When offering things, offer things small enough=\r\n (depending on the size of fire) so that they burn fully.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Secondly=\r\n, things offered should have enough air circulation. Even if I offer small =\r\nitems, things stuck in the middle of a big pile do not get enough oxygen to=\r\n burn. Offering materials at a reasonable pace and spreading them throughou=\r\nt the firepit, may help.\n&gt;\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Even firewood logs will burn better and=\r\n brighter if they have air circulation. If a wood log touches fire pit bott=\r\nom/walls only at its two edges and is suspended in air elsewhere, it will b=\r\nurn better because of air supply. Otherwise, edges of the portion without a=\r\nir circulation may keep releasing smoke.\n&gt;\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;As things burn, if you =\r\nturn them around or mix them up so that everything burns well (tongs may be=\r\n used), it can help you burn everything well.\n&gt;=C2=A0When I offer poornahut=\r\ni (a whole dry coconut) in my homam, I pre-arrange burnt wood coals in a st=\r\nructure that has nice air flow. When coconut is placed atop those coals, it=\r\n does not crush everything (in which case, some stuff under coconut or bott=\r\nom of coconut may burn fully by the time fire goes off), but gets suspended=\r\n on the coals with most of the coconut getting air circulation. It burns ni=\r\ncely from all sides, including the bottom. If this is not possible, you may=\r\n want to turn the poornahuti around in the middle (while there is still fir=\r\ne) and perhaps change its position/place (and offer a little more ghee then=\r\n). In my case, I go into one-hour japam after poornahuti and do not want to=\r\n stop meditation in the middle to take care of poornahuti. So I arrange thi=\r\nngs nicely beforehand. The way it is placed, it just burns completely and e=\r\nverything offered before also burns completely, by the time fire goes off b=\r\ny itself.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;It is a matter of understanding the dynamics of how fire=\r\n and oxygen interact to burn materials and when smoke comes. One should try=\r\n to learn from experience and\n draw common sense lessons.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Regarding shreema.org recommendation (&quot;We extinguish the =\r\nfire during the Purnahuti. Pour milk over the burning coals&quot;, &quot;Milk stands =\r\nfor the ocean of consciousness =E2=80=93 pure, white, the absence of all co=\r\nlors, attitudes. After the fire has purified all impurities, it \nis extingu=\r\nished with pure consciousness.&quot;):\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Such a practice may exist in som=\r\ne traditions. In my humble, but firm, opinion, this practice is based on ig=\r\nnorance and worth ignoring. When discussing this specific recommendation an=\r\nd the quotes above, Dr Svoboda wrote to me, &quot;I definitely do not endorse qu=\r\nenching homa at its end. Neither did Vimalananda&quot;.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;I believe Shree=\r\n Ma and Swamiji have their hearts in the right place and doing good dharmik=\r\n work. I do admire their work and wish them well. But this advice of theirs=\r\n is simply nonsensical. First of all, milk is not a symbol of pure consciou=\r\nsness. Milk has a specific taste and color (sweetness and white) and not re=\r\nally a symbol of guna-less pure consciousness. Secondly, fire is the symbol=\r\n of Divinity and you should let it process your offerings completely and gi=\r\nve the results in due time. You can&#39;t try to force things. Pouring milk und=\r\ner the pretext that it is &quot;pure consciousness&quot; is akin to doing some sadhan=\r\na and pretending that you are now in samadhi. That only results in delusion=\r\ns and theatrics and not real samadhi. If you want real samadhi, you need tr=\r\nue surrender. True surrender requires infinite patience.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Never eve=\r\nr extinguish homam fire. If there are practical limitations on when fire sh=\r\nould go off (e.g. you need to leave), maintain a small enough fire and offe=\r\nr poornahuti early enough, so that fire goes off by itself by the needed ti=\r\nme. But you can&#39;t forcefully extinguish it when fire is still burning.\n&gt;=C2=\r\n=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Someone I know does homam outside and leaves =\r\nfor work. Though fire goes off before he leaves, there will be red coals fo=\r\nr a much longer time. Wind can make small coals fly off and so, for safety,=\r\n he covers the homa kundam with a tightly wrapped aluminum foil. That also =\r\nis like extinguishing fire because you are turning off oxygen supply that c=\r\nan help fire (resident in red coals) to burn things further and consume the=\r\nm. If you make 2 small holes in the foil cover to keep oxygen flowing, with=\r\n holes being small enough that solid things cannot fly off through them, it=\r\n is safe and, at the same time, allows Agni to consume as much as he wants!=\r\n Once you invite Agni, offer only as much as you want Him to consume, but d=\r\no let Him consume all of it. Don&#39;t stop him forcefully in the middle.\n&gt;\n&gt;=\r\n=C2=A0*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&lt;&lt;Also I am keen in knowing , does attending =\r\nhavan also burn karmas ...I mean not giving any aahuti but just attending h=\r\navan&gt;&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;As per &quot;Parasara Madhaveeyam&quot; (commentary on Parasara Smriti - au=\r\nthority for this age - by celebrated Madhavacharya, brother of Sayanacharya=\r\n who wrote the\n celebrated commentaries on Veda), a ritual performed by one=\r\nself is 1,000,000 times more powe